        <h1>LeetCode 762: Prime Number of Set Bits in Binary Representation (C++)</h1>
        <div class="problem-description">
            <p><strong>Problem:</strong>
                Given two integers left and right, return the count of numbers in the inclusive range [left, right]
                having a prime number of set bits in their binary representation. A set bit is a bit in the binary
                representation of a number that has a value of 1. Recall that a number is prime if it has exactly two
                divisors: 1 and itself.
            </p>
            <p><strong>Example:</strong>
                Input: left = 6, right = 10<br>
                Output: 4<br>
                Explanation: 6 (110) has 2 set bits, 7 (111) has 3, 8 (1000) has 1, 9 (1001) has 2, 10 (1010) has 2.
                Numbers with prime set bits: 6, 7, 9, 10 = 4 numbers.
            </p>
        </div>
        <div class="code-container">
            <button class="copy-button" onclick="copyCode(this)">Copy Code</button>
            <pre><code class="language-cpp">class Solution {
public:
    int countPrimeSetBits(int leftBound, int rightBound) {
        
        // Pre-mark prime counts up to 19 (max possible set bits)
        bool isPrimeCount[20] = {false};
        int primeList[] = {2, 3, 5, 7, 11, 13, 17, 19};
        
        for(int &amp;primeVal : primeList)
            isPrimeCount[primeVal] = true;
        
        int total = 0;
        
        for(int num = leftBound; num &lt;= rightBound; num++){
            int bitCount = __builtin_popcount(num);  // Fast built-in bit count
            if(isPrimeCount[bitCount])
                total++;
        }
        
        return total;
    }
};</code></pre>
